  "prompt": "What is stannic hydroxide?",
  "response": "Stannic hydroxide, also known as tin(IV) hydroxide, is a chemical compound with the formula Sn(OH)\u2084. It is an amphoteric hydroxide, meaning it can react with both acids and bases. Stannic hydroxide is often encountered as a gel-like substance or as a solid precipitate. It is not a well-defined compound and usually refers to hydrated tin(IV) oxide, SnO\u2082\u00b7nH\u2082O.\n\nIn practice, stannic hydroxide can be prepared by adding a base, such as sodium hydroxide, to a solution containing tin(IV) ions. This causes the hydroxide to precipitate out of solution. Due to its amphoteric nature, stannic hydroxide can dissolve in strong acids to form stannic salts, or it can react with strong bases to form stannates.\n\nStannic hydroxide has some applications in the materials and chemical industries, where it can be used as a precursor to other tin compounds, and in some cases, as a catalyst or adsorbent.",
